It's a Jewish tradition to do things to keep people's memories alive.

00:04:44.579 --> 00:04:48.779
So the hats are all for Cindy Bailey.

00:04:48.779 --> 00:04:51.739
So that's kind of who I am, where I came from.

00:04:51.739 --> 00:04:57.500
I have undergraduate degrees in math and statistics, undergraduate in math, graduate in math and

00:04:57.500 --> 00:05:05.579
graduate in statistics from New York schools, and then ended up at Intel because I was living

00:05:05.579 --> 00:05:10.459
on the West Coast where I did process control in their factories and performance analysis.

00:05:10.459 --> 00:05:17.339
I bounced around a number of different industries, but kind of my common theme in my career has

00:05:17.339 --> 00:05:24.059
been helping people use their data, be it manufacturing data, banking data, pharmaceutical

00:05:24.059 --> 00:05:25.059
data in my case.

00:05:25.059 --> 00:05:27.100
I was a financial advisor for a while.

00:05:27.100 --> 00:05:34.220
I'm fascinated by why it is that people have data and then don't use it, myself included.

00:05:34.220 --> 00:05:38.859
We all know how to be rich and thin, and we don't do it, right?

00:05:38.859 --> 00:05:46.779
So I'm as interested in the analysis as I am interested in how do you present analysis

00:05:46.779 --> 00:05:50.059
in a way that action will actually happen?

00:05:50.059 --> 00:05:55.660
So I spend a lot of time trying to think about that, and why is it that people are so adverse

00:05:55.660 --> 00:05:58.820
to looking at data and understanding it?

00:05:58.820 --> 00:06:01.059
I love it.

00:06:01.059 --> 00:06:05.179
How did you make the leap from university to data?

00:06:05.179 --> 00:06:11.739
What was your sort of like initial thought process in I want to go into data or did this

00:06:11.739 --> 00:06:13.660
kind of creep up on you?

00:06:13.660 --> 00:06:16.739
So let me start with how I ended up as a math major.

00:06:16.739 --> 00:06:18.660
My mother was a philosopher.

00:06:18.660 --> 00:06:21.059
I didn't want to do the hard sciences.

00:06:21.059 --> 00:06:24.899
I was told I couldn't write because I had a learning disability, so there went all the

00:06:24.899 --> 00:06:28.420
humanities and I didn't like physics.

00:06:29.019 --> 00:06:33.380
And computer science, because of the learning disabilities, was outside of my scope.

00:06:33.380 --> 00:06:38.540
Prior to modern computer environments where everything is color-coded, if you don't read

00:06:38.540 --> 00:06:40.700
syntax, you can't code.

00:06:40.700 --> 00:06:45.899
So I'm old enough that a VI editor and I were not friends.

00:06:45.899 --> 00:06:48.220
So I ended up in math by default.

00:06:48.220 --> 00:06:52.500
I think I'm the only person in the world who ended up with a theoretical math degree because

00:06:52.500 --> 00:06:56.140
it was the only thing I could figure out how I could get through.

00:06:56.140 --> 00:06:59.500
I got kicked out of graduate school because of those children I mentioned.

00:06:59.500 --> 00:07:02.700
They told me I wasn't sufficiently focused.

00:07:02.700 --> 00:07:12.739
And in Portland, where I landed, Intel was the largest person, was the largest employer.

00:07:12.739 --> 00:07:16.579
In graduate school, because I went to Columbia, I actually got a statistics degree and had

00:07:16.579 --> 00:07:20.859
seen one data set with 20 rows of data in it.

00:07:20.859 --> 00:07:25.660
So I learned data on the fly because it was, I needed a job.

00:07:26.179 --> 00:07:27.179
So I called up hiring managers.

00:07:27.179 --> 00:07:33.220
I called up three hiring managers a week off an Intel listing that I had gotten from an

00:07:33.220 --> 00:07:38.100
internal source and talked until someone said, oh, you can do statistics, come do process

00:07:38.100 --> 00:07:39.100
control.

00:07:39.100 --> 00:07:41.660
And I said, okay.

00:07:41.660 --> 00:07:45.179
So lots of just kind of what happened.

00:07:45.179 --> 00:07:47.859
And then I've stayed in data because it's fascinating to me.

00:07:47.859 --> 00:07:50.660
It speaks to me and I can do it.

00:07:50.660 --> 00:07:52.660
Thank you.

00:07:53.660 --> 00:07:57.859
Well, Nahama, I was wondering to get us started here as well, if you could tell us a little

00:07:57.859 --> 00:08:02.779
bit about the concept of relevant analytics and what it means.

00:08:02.779 --> 00:08:03.779
Yeah.

00:08:03.779 --> 00:08:07.859
So it's easy to do analytics, right?

00:08:07.859 --> 00:08:10.260
You take a bunch of data and we've all done that.

00:08:10.260 --> 00:08:14.260
You open up a data set and you're like, oh, cool.

00:08:14.260 --> 00:08:15.540
I can take a standard deviation.

00:08:15.540 --> 00:08:18.179
I can take a descriptive statistic.

00:08:18.179 --> 00:08:19.179
I can plot it.

00:08:19.179 --> 00:08:20.980
I can do all sorts of stuff.

00:08:21.019 --> 00:08:22.220
And then the question is, okay, great.

00:08:22.220 --> 00:08:23.220
Now what?

00:08:23.220 --> 00:08:26.420
I'll give an example from Intel.

00:08:26.420 --> 00:08:33.900
Years ago, I did a cool 3D model of transistor density on Intel and competitive chips.

00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:34.900
Looked beautiful.

00:08:34.900 --> 00:08:39.219
It was in math, in a cool graphing software.

00:08:39.219 --> 00:08:40.619
It looked like a city.

00:08:40.619 --> 00:08:43.140
And someone looked at me and said, so what am I going to do with this?

00:08:43.140 --> 00:08:45.260
I said, I don't know.

00:08:45.260 --> 00:08:46.979
And a lot of analytical people say that.

00:08:46.979 --> 00:08:49.260
They say, well, I don't know.

00:08:49.260 --> 00:08:50.260
It's data.

00:08:50.260 --> 00:08:52.780
I'm not going to do anything with it.

00:08:52.780 --> 00:08:59.700
I am really focused now on kind of the concept that technology on its own doesn't do you

00:08:59.700 --> 00:09:00.700
any good.

00:09:00.700 --> 00:09:01.700
I hate to say it.

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:03.900
You guys can write the best app on the planet.

00:09:03.900 --> 00:09:05.260
It can make coffee.

00:09:05.260 --> 00:09:07.659
It can do everything anyone ever wants.

00:09:07.659 --> 00:09:11.739
But if it doesn't answer an actual business question, it's not going to help.

00:09:11.739 --> 00:09:19.820
So what typically happens in most data spaces is that people spend all this money on this

00:09:20.380 --> 00:09:21.380
technology.

00:09:21.380 --> 00:09:22.380
Nobody knows how to use it.

00:09:22.380 --> 00:09:26.780
And then the fact that no one uses it gets blamed on bad change management.

00:09:26.780 --> 00:09:29.020
And well, the users didn't want to change, right?

00:09:29.020 --> 00:09:32.900
And some of you guys are on video, nod your heads, right?

00:09:32.900 --> 00:09:33.900
You've heard this, right?

00:09:33.900 --> 00:09:37.979
If the users would just use it, it would have fixed all their problems.

00:09:37.979 --> 00:09:41.099
And the users won't use it because it's about 80% correct.

00:09:41.099 --> 00:09:45.460
In most cases, if you're really, really, really good and you're not talking to end users every

00:09:45.460 --> 00:09:49.900
single day, you're going to be at best 80% relevant.

00:09:49.900 --> 00:09:52.979
And that's not enough for them to make business decisions.

00:09:52.979 --> 00:10:00.179
So I'm talking about a model nowadays of start with business context.

00:10:00.179 --> 00:10:04.460
So what are the business questions that the business needs to answer?

00:10:04.460 --> 00:10:07.859
And then what are the data that actually supports those questions?

00:10:07.859 --> 00:10:09.419
Not the data that you can get.

00:10:09.419 --> 00:10:18.219
So let me give an example from a conversation I had with someone outside of work.

00:10:18.219 --> 00:10:23.900
Call center asked a question, how many consecutive calls do you have?

00:10:23.900 --> 00:10:25.460
How many contiguous calls?

00:10:25.460 --> 00:10:27.780
How many calls do you have at the same time?

00:10:27.780 --> 00:10:31.179
Because they needed to know how many call center employees to have.

00:10:31.179 --> 00:10:33.299
So the data people gave them what?

00:10:33.299 --> 00:10:39.780
They gave them the average duration of a call.

00:10:39.780 --> 00:10:42.500
So how many calls do you have in 15 minutes?

00:10:42.500 --> 00:10:47.260
How many calls come in in 15 minutes was actually, I think, what they were given because that

00:10:47.260 --> 00:10:51.299
was what was easy to pull out of the data warehouse.

00:10:51.299 --> 00:10:55.820
But the number of calls that come in in 15 minutes on a call center didn't capture the

00:10:55.820 --> 00:11:01.780
long tail, the extremely long calls that were for customers who were stuck someplace and

00:11:01.780 --> 00:11:04.460
desperately needed to talk to someone.

00:11:04.460 --> 00:11:08.739
So they hired the wrong number of call center people.

00:11:08.739 --> 00:11:14.659
And the business was now in a problem because they couldn't meet their customer needs, right?

00:11:14.659 --> 00:11:17.380
They had a great answer to the wrong problem.

00:11:17.380 --> 00:11:20.859
So that's an example of understanding the problem.

00:11:20.859 --> 00:11:26.539
And I've been in multiple business situations where someone will say, hey, here's the question

00:11:26.539 --> 00:11:27.539
I have.

00:11:27.539 --> 00:11:31.460
And then they go back and forth and back and forth.

00:11:32.140 --> 00:11:34.979
But really, the data people just say, here's the data we have.

00:11:34.979 --> 00:11:37.539
Can't you use our data to answer that question?

00:11:37.539 --> 00:11:38.539
And the answer is no.

00:11:38.539 --> 00:11:40.260
The answer is no.

00:11:40.260 --> 00:11:42.940
That question isn't going to answer what the business needs.

00:11:42.940 --> 00:11:45.500
And it doesn't help if that's easy data to get to.

00:11:45.500 --> 00:11:49.940
You have to then figure out how to get the right data to answer those questions.

00:11:49.940 --> 00:11:54.539
And then be really transparent to your business about what question you are answering.

00:11:54.539 --> 00:12:01.900
Because people's livelihoods and the business is at stake based off bad analysis.

00:12:01.900 --> 00:12:05.539
So that's kind of this concept of how do you do business relevant.

00:12:05.539 --> 00:12:08.299
You need to understand what are the questions and prioritize them.

00:12:08.299 --> 00:12:11.140
Not all questions are as important.

00:12:11.140 --> 00:12:13.619
You need to understand why that question was important, right?

00:12:13.619 --> 00:12:20.340
If this was about hiring call centers, employees, so that a business that in this particular

00:12:20.380 --> 00:12:26.380
case, meeting customer needs when things went bad was critically important to people.

00:12:26.380 --> 00:12:28.820
It wasn't, oh, you could wait two weeks.

00:12:28.820 --> 00:12:30.820
No, that wasn't an answer.

00:12:30.820 --> 00:12:35.820
You needed to understand why that question was important as well.

00:12:35.820 --> 00:12:38.419
So you have to know the priority and know what your data is.

00:12:38.419 --> 00:12:44.460
Once you've got your highest priority questions, you answer the highest priority question for

00:12:44.460 --> 00:12:49.780
which you have data first, and then you build a data pipeline to put in all the other data

00:12:49.780 --> 00:12:50.780
that you need.

00:12:50.780 --> 00:12:52.260
I love it.

00:12:52.260 --> 00:12:57.380
I think this follows on to something I've heard you say before, which is actually that

00:12:57.380 --> 00:13:04.059
you believe business people can outperform programmers because they have most of the

00:13:04.059 --> 00:13:07.140
time because they have that background, that understanding of the question.

00:13:07.140 --> 00:13:09.380
Can you talk a little bit about that?

00:13:09.380 --> 00:13:10.380
Yeah.

00:13:10.380 --> 00:13:14.380
So I love computer science programmers who can program.

00:13:14.380 --> 00:13:21.140
The challenge is that if I take a consultant, let's take a consultant rather than a generic

00:13:21.140 --> 00:13:22.140
full-time programmer.

00:13:22.140 --> 00:13:29.219
So if I take a consultant who's working in my environment and I throw a problem at them,

00:13:29.219 --> 00:13:31.299
I need to give them every single little detail.

00:13:31.299 --> 00:13:33.299
I was on a call earlier today.

00:13:33.299 --> 00:13:38.460
Someone was like, oh, I've got three data files, and they asked the data guy for access

00:13:38.460 --> 00:13:42.340
to the data and the data files, and the guy's like, I don't know what you're talking about.

00:13:42.340 --> 00:13:44.380
These are end system files.

00:13:44.380 --> 00:13:48.140
Some of them were manually made up by the business.

00:13:48.140 --> 00:13:53.219
So he's off asking questions that don't make any sense.

00:13:53.219 --> 00:13:59.539
In my experience, if I have a business person or a business curious technologist, that's

00:13:59.539 --> 00:14:00.539
the same thing, right?

00:14:00.539 --> 00:14:07.739
So someone who's curious about technology, and they are curious about the business.

00:14:07.739 --> 00:14:12.419
Someone who's curious about the business and knows some technology, what they are able

00:14:12.419 --> 00:14:20.739
to do is program what needs to be programmed, and they don't need to have a full-time business

00:14:20.739 --> 00:14:22.820
person babysitting them.

00:14:22.820 --> 00:14:26.960
And that full-time business person doesn't understand the technology, so then the relationship

00:14:26.960 --> 00:14:28.299
gets really frustrating, right?

00:14:28.299 --> 00:14:34.380
You've got a person who's using Excel, so think horses and buggies on a country road,

00:14:34.380 --> 00:14:38.739
and you've got a guy driving a Porsche, and the guy in the Porsche is saying, well, where

00:14:38.739 --> 00:14:40.979
do you want the radio?

00:14:40.979 --> 00:14:45.580
And the guy in the horse and buggy is saying, radio, what's a radio?

00:14:45.580 --> 00:14:48.659
And the third time they say, what's a radio, and the guy says, oh, don't worry about it,

00:14:48.659 --> 00:14:51.080
I'll just put it to the right of the dashboard.

00:14:51.080 --> 00:14:56.179
They stop asking the question, and so now you've got this car that makes no sense, but

00:14:56.179 --> 00:14:58.739
it's the requirements, but you gave me requirements.

00:14:58.739 --> 00:15:01.700
I didn't know what requirements I was giving you.

00:15:01.700 --> 00:15:03.820
And then they're written in weird language, right?

00:15:03.820 --> 00:15:10.700
So that whole process that was established, I think, to support, right, why did we do

00:15:10.700 --> 00:15:11.700
that?

00:15:11.700 --> 00:15:15.659
We did all this requirements gathering and documentation and everything so that you could

00:15:15.659 --> 00:15:19.900
have one person writing requirements, and we could twirl the programming at any trained

00:15:19.900 --> 00:15:25.320
monkey, so to speak, no offense to any of you guys, to write code.

00:15:25.320 --> 00:15:29.059
And if you just cut out that whole thing, and you take someone who knows what needs

00:15:29.059 --> 00:15:33.380
to be done, give them some broad context, they're like, oh, yeah, okay, I know how to

00:15:33.940 --> 00:15:39.460
drive a car, then we go around the block, they'll just get there much faster.

00:15:39.460 --> 00:15:45.979
And so in my experience, a person who's doing writing code 30% of their time, who's willing

00:15:45.979 --> 00:15:52.460
to write code, will outperform a full-time programmer every single time.

00:15:52.460 --> 00:15:55.140
Thank you for that analogy.

00:15:55.140 --> 00:16:00.020
I want to make sure I go over to some of the anonymous questions as well, and I see someone

00:16:00.020 --> 00:16:05.940
asked earlier, what do you think are best practices for teaching people statistics?

00:16:05.940 --> 00:16:13.340
I've seen either not real world, too simple, or too theoretical, not convenient, is what

00:16:13.340 --> 00:16:14.340
they said.

00:16:14.340 --> 00:16:21.059
So I used to teach math and statistics at the university level.

00:16:21.140 --> 00:16:31.020
I think that for each statistical concept, you need to have a very simple canonical example.

00:16:31.020 --> 00:16:35.059
So let me take an example.

00:16:35.059 --> 00:16:36.380
What's the average, right?

00:16:36.380 --> 00:16:37.380
So what's an average?

00:16:37.380 --> 00:16:39.940
Well, it's a physical measurement.

00:16:39.940 --> 00:16:44.099
I'm looking at my crochet hook, and if I put my finger here, that's the average, right?

00:16:44.099 --> 00:16:46.539
There's half the amount of weight is on each side of the crochet hook.

00:16:46.539 --> 00:16:48.820
I'm assuming you guys can see my thing, right?

00:16:48.820 --> 00:16:50.619
So now I know what an average is.

00:16:51.179 --> 00:16:55.340
If I then say, well, you know what, if I have this crochet hook and I've got a long tail,

00:16:55.340 --> 00:16:59.020
meaning I've got data all the way out here, it's clear that my average is then going to

00:16:59.020 --> 00:17:01.659
get pushed, right?

00:17:01.659 --> 00:17:03.619
My scale is going to get pushed down.

00:17:03.619 --> 00:17:07.699
So you need to have a very simple explanation in your head.

00:17:07.699 --> 00:17:12.140
Then you can look at what does the data look like?

00:17:12.140 --> 00:17:18.900
I'm a firm believer in open up a tablet pad and actually do some math by hand a couple

00:17:18.900 --> 00:17:21.540
times with some small numbers.

00:17:21.540 --> 00:17:24.380
That's really helpful.

00:17:24.380 --> 00:17:26.660
And then ask.

00:17:26.660 --> 00:17:31.859
So there's how to actually perform the statistical tests, and those are relatively straightforward

00:17:31.859 --> 00:17:33.780
once you get some examples.

00:17:33.780 --> 00:17:39.500
Like a standard deviation is number of average deviations away from where you are, like how

00:17:39.500 --> 00:17:43.380
far are you from a center of mass, for example.

00:17:43.380 --> 00:17:51.060
But you really need to bring in data and then exercise it and plot it.

00:17:51.060 --> 00:17:56.819
There is no data without a, there's no statistical analysis without a data plot.

00:17:56.819 --> 00:18:00.699
And if you plot all of your data and then run your statistical analysis, the data will

00:18:00.699 --> 00:18:01.699
make sense.

00:18:01.699 --> 00:18:03.939
Or if it's wrong, you'll see it.

00:18:03.939 --> 00:18:06.099
So start with a simple example.

00:18:06.099 --> 00:18:08.099
Always have that simple example in your head, right?

00:18:08.099 --> 00:18:09.780
What's concave up in a calculus problem?

00:18:09.780 --> 00:18:13.060
Well, it looks like this, and that's concave down.

00:18:13.739 --> 00:18:17.900
And then you can figure out if it's x squared or 2x, if the second derivative is positive

00:18:17.900 --> 00:18:18.900
or negative.

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:23.180
You can recompute the second example and regenerate the rules.

00:18:23.180 --> 00:18:30.099
I don't know if that answered anyone's question on how to learn statistics, but.

00:18:30.099 --> 00:18:32.859
And then find data that means something to you, right?

00:18:32.859 --> 00:18:34.579
If you're into sports, do sports.

00:18:34.579 --> 00:18:36.979
If you're into woodworking, do woodworking.

00:18:36.979 --> 00:18:41.420
Find something that you can understand the data, because the problem with statistics

00:18:41.500 --> 00:18:45.500
is not the computation, it's understanding the underlying data.

00:18:45.500 --> 00:18:48.900
And if it's something you care about, then you'll know about it.

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:50.500
What's an average height for a horse jump?

00:18:50.500 --> 00:18:52.819
I'm sure my daughter would know what the answer to that is.

00:18:52.819 --> 00:18:56.739
I would have, I could come up with six meters and be like, that sounds a little high.

00:18:56.739 --> 00:19:01.380
And she would tell me, yeah, it's high.

00:19:01.380 --> 00:19:06.300
So I know we talked a bit already about business background.

00:19:06.300 --> 00:19:11.579
So for someone on the call who's perhaps an aspiring data professional or trying to

00:19:11.579 --> 00:19:18.420
get better at this, how would you recommend acquiring the business background needed to

00:19:18.420 --> 00:19:19.420
help them succeed?

00:19:19.420 --> 00:19:20.420
Yeah.

00:19:20.420 --> 00:19:24.459
So the first one is be curious, be curious, be curious, be curious.

00:19:24.459 --> 00:19:29.500
Most of you guys, I am guessing, because most smart people were like this, asked a ton of

00:19:29.500 --> 00:19:31.180
questions when they were kids, right?

00:19:31.180 --> 00:19:32.180
Raise your hands.

00:19:32.300 --> 00:19:33.300
Tons and tons of questions.

00:19:33.300 --> 00:19:38.819
And around five or six, you were told to stop asking questions.

00:19:38.819 --> 00:19:42.020
You were in school and there was no time to ask your teacher a million questions.

00:19:42.020 --> 00:19:43.020
Is this true?

00:19:43.020 --> 00:19:44.020
Thumbs up.

00:19:44.020 --> 00:19:45.020
Give me some.

00:19:45.020 --> 00:19:46.819
I'm used to some feedback, right?

00:19:46.819 --> 00:19:47.819
Yeah.

00:19:47.819 --> 00:19:48.819
Okay.

00:19:48.819 --> 00:19:54.060
So go back to your five or six year old brain and ask questions and ask questions and ask

00:19:54.060 --> 00:19:55.060
questions.

00:19:55.060 --> 00:19:59.859
Go find someone in your business calls who seems to be interested in the data and say,

00:19:59.859 --> 00:20:02.739
hey, can you explain this to me?

00:20:02.739 --> 00:20:04.819
Can you tell me what's going on?

00:20:04.819 --> 00:20:06.579
Would you walk through it with me?

00:20:06.579 --> 00:20:11.300
It turns out that business professionals are the same as data professionals.

00:20:11.300 --> 00:20:15.099
Almost anyone will do anything for a free cup of coffee.

00:20:15.099 --> 00:20:16.380
And you can do that over Zoom.

00:20:16.380 --> 00:20:22.859
Send them a Starbucks card over Zoom and say, hey, can I pick your brain for a cup of coffee?

00:20:22.859 --> 00:20:25.939
And here's what I don't even know what Starbucks costs now.

00:20:25.939 --> 00:20:29.060
It's more than five bucks, but whatever it is, right?

00:20:29.060 --> 00:20:33.219
Can I buy you a cup of coffee and pick your brain and ask questions?

00:20:33.219 --> 00:20:39.099
And then at the end of that, ask who else you should talk to because they'll give you

00:20:39.099 --> 00:20:40.739
a list of other people to talk to.

00:20:40.739 --> 00:20:43.099
So just build a tree of people to talk to.

00:20:43.099 --> 00:20:47.619
But the most, most important thing to do is after you finish taking someone's 20 or 30

00:20:47.619 --> 00:20:53.500
minutes and decide how long it's going to be and end the call at that time, ask them

00:20:53.500 --> 00:20:58.300
at the end of that call if there's anything you can do for them.

00:20:58.300 --> 00:21:01.219
Because all those say no, so it's a cheap question to ask.

00:21:01.219 --> 00:21:04.619
And if they don't say no, then you're helpful to them, right?

00:21:04.619 --> 00:21:08.819
And they will never forget you because almost nobody asks them if there's anything that

00:21:08.819 --> 00:21:11.859
you could do for them and then send them a thank you note.

00:21:11.859 --> 00:21:14.060
I love that.

00:21:14.060 --> 00:21:15.060
Right?

00:21:15.060 --> 00:21:19.020
So just basic stuff your grandmother would have told you, maybe.

00:21:19.020 --> 00:21:22.900
Why is it so hard to ask for people inside your org for their time?

00:21:22.900 --> 00:21:27.500
I feel like it's easier outside for some reason.

00:21:27.500 --> 00:21:34.459
I have VP level people in my industry outside of my corporation who will give me time faster

00:21:34.459 --> 00:21:38.979
than my current management.

00:21:38.979 --> 00:21:40.540
I think there's two reasons.

00:21:40.540 --> 00:21:48.380
One is that the fear of asking someone in your food chain, right, who's senior to you,

00:21:48.380 --> 00:21:50.699
you feel like there's a risk to your job, right?

00:21:50.699 --> 00:21:53.180
Is it safe to ask a question?

00:21:53.180 --> 00:21:56.180
And if you go outside of the organization, you don't have to worry about psychological

00:21:56.180 --> 00:22:03.579
safety because who cares, right, if they think you're stupid or don't know what you're

00:22:03.579 --> 00:22:04.579
talking about.

00:22:04.579 --> 00:22:09.819
But that's, again, it comes back to can you, you just have to, you have to learn to ask

00:22:09.819 --> 00:22:16.540
because if you don't learn to ask the questions, then you're never going to learn the business

00:22:16.540 --> 00:22:22.979
and you will be always competing against someone who programs against the SPAC.

00:22:22.979 --> 00:22:27.939
But we all know that people who program against the SPAC are not very expensive typically.

00:22:27.939 --> 00:22:31.020
Yeah, this is a great, this is a great conversation.

00:22:31.020 --> 00:22:33.619
I feel like it all comes back to curiosity.

00:22:33.619 --> 00:22:36.260
It's curiosity, curiosity and bravery, right?

00:22:36.260 --> 00:22:38.300
You have to just be willing to ask questions.

00:22:38.300 --> 00:22:40.660
That five-year-old you, what is it they said?

00:22:40.660 --> 00:22:45.099
I had someone said to me, no two-year-old ever, year and a half-year-old, I don't know,

00:22:45.099 --> 00:22:50.900
in my family we walked late, but no one-year-old ever said, oh, I fell down 10 times, I guess

00:22:50.900 --> 00:22:52.939
I just won't learn how to walk.

00:22:52.939 --> 00:22:53.939
Yeah.

00:22:53.939 --> 00:22:54.939
Right?

00:22:54.939 --> 00:23:00.380
And I think that there's a little bit of work that has to be done to cultivate that mindset.

00:23:00.380 --> 00:23:04.939
And there's a Slido question that is really in line with this, I'd love to ask it.

00:23:04.939 --> 00:23:08.819
So it says, your bio mentions that you create innovative solutions.

00:23:08.819 --> 00:23:15.540
So do you have any particular tools or methods that you can recommend to help stimulate creative

00:23:15.540 --> 00:23:18.660
thinking or I would say stimulate curiosity?

00:23:19.180 --> 00:23:26.300
Yeah, so let's get some other side topic that I love talking about, which is productivity.

00:23:26.300 --> 00:23:30.020
The first thing I'm going to tell you guys is get eight hours of sleep at night, preferably

00:23:30.020 --> 00:23:39.699
consecutively, get some exercise and do not work more than eight hours a day on average.

00:23:39.699 --> 00:23:42.900
You will not be creative if you're constantly working.

00:23:42.900 --> 00:23:46.939
And the way you get creativity is to stop, stop and do something else.

00:23:46.939 --> 00:23:53.699
So I have solved more math problems or other types of problems, learning woodworking.

00:23:53.699 --> 00:23:56.099
Over COVID, I learned woodworking.

00:23:56.099 --> 00:24:01.060
And one of my biggest first insights was my daughter, seven years old at the time, looks

00:24:01.060 --> 00:24:04.540
at me and says, can I use the power tools?

00:24:04.540 --> 00:24:08.459
She had brothers, for some reason, no one had offered to let her use a power drill before.

00:24:08.459 --> 00:24:12.939
And I was like, whoa, if my daughter doesn't know how to ask for something, I wonder who

00:24:12.939 --> 00:24:15.260
on my team isn't asking for anything.

00:24:15.260 --> 00:24:19.380
I went back and turns out no one on my team was asking for anything.

00:24:19.380 --> 00:24:23.339
So we had a lot of conversations about, okay, ask for opportunities.

00:24:23.339 --> 00:24:26.739
What does it look like to ask for an opportunity?

00:24:26.739 --> 00:24:29.500
Are there ways to set up the power tools so you don't hurt yourself?

00:24:29.500 --> 00:24:34.180
The answer is sure, we can put safe guardrails around asking.

00:24:34.180 --> 00:24:40.060
But the number of things that you can learn by doing something else, and in particular

00:24:40.060 --> 00:24:45.180
doing a physical, I love making things because there's nothing like making something to get

00:24:45.180 --> 00:24:49.020
your brain wired differently.

00:24:49.020 --> 00:24:55.060
Some people like gardening, I don't, but like making stuff, painting stuff, solving problems,

00:24:55.060 --> 00:25:00.180
it just gives you a space to back off and then you've got something you've accomplished,

00:25:00.180 --> 00:25:01.180
which is also really cool.

00:25:01.180 --> 00:25:05.540
It's really hard to show that you've done something in a knowledge job, but at the end

00:25:05.540 --> 00:25:11.500
of the day, if you finished a floor, you've done something.

00:25:11.500 --> 00:25:20.140
I have on YouTube someplace, I have a whole thing on creativity that I did with, I worked

00:25:20.140 --> 00:25:21.619
with a creatives coach.

00:25:21.619 --> 00:25:25.939
And so you can look, just Google me, you'll find it with Julie Geller.

00:25:25.939 --> 00:25:31.660
I worked with a creatives coach, it was great, just what's the creative process, huge improvement.

00:25:31.660 --> 00:25:36.780
But the biggest thing with productivity is to stop, stop, take breaks, don't do anything.

00:25:36.979 --> 00:25:42.060
That does not mean doom scroll and scroll on your phone, like shut your brain down.

00:25:42.060 --> 00:25:46.459
If you're scrolling on your phone, you're not stopping, you're running on idle and getting

00:25:46.459 --> 00:25:47.459
nowhere.

00:25:47.459 --> 00:25:51.780
You're just burning gas, creating fumes and doing no, getting absolutely nowhere.

00:25:51.780 --> 00:25:53.339
So you need to just stop.

00:25:53.339 --> 00:25:57.380
At some point in your day, you have to say, I'm done, I'm done, I'm stopped.

00:25:57.380 --> 00:26:02.939
Read a book, crochet, talk to a kid, play pickleball, whatever it is that you do, walk

00:26:02.939 --> 00:26:05.939
around the block.

00:26:05.939 --> 00:26:10.619
You'll be way more creative the next day than if you work through a problem.

00:26:10.619 --> 00:26:13.579
That is fantastic, fantastic advice.

00:26:13.579 --> 00:26:17.540
And I can really relate to that feeling of going, I don't feel like I've done anything

00:26:17.540 --> 00:26:18.540
today.

00:26:18.540 --> 00:26:19.540
I had a bunch of meetings.

00:26:19.540 --> 00:26:21.819
I have no physical product to show, right?

00:26:21.819 --> 00:26:25.859
I didn't refloor the living room, I didn't fill the shelf.

00:26:25.859 --> 00:26:30.500
Let me give one more thing to do though, is pick your optimal time of the day.

00:26:30.500 --> 00:26:33.380
And I hate to tell this to everyone who's not a morning person, it's first thing in

00:26:33.380 --> 00:26:35.540
the morning for most people.

00:26:35.540 --> 00:26:41.900
Pick an hour and a half, get on a tool like Focusmate, decide what you're going to do

00:26:41.900 --> 00:26:44.880
and think for an hour and a half.

00:26:44.880 --> 00:26:52.380
You will get, most managers do less than 11 minutes of work an hour.

00:26:52.380 --> 00:26:57.619
So someone's done the math, you can do an entire month's of work in one day with these

00:26:57.619 --> 00:26:59.660
power psych focus sessions.

00:26:59.660 --> 00:27:05.699
And it's 75 minutes, no one can focus for more than about 90, so 65, 75 minute power

00:27:05.699 --> 00:27:10.420
session of, I know exactly what I'm going to do, shut off everything on your screen

00:27:10.420 --> 00:27:13.260
except for that and focus on it.

00:27:13.260 --> 00:27:16.420
Then you can go do the meetings because you've already done your day.

00:27:16.420 --> 00:27:21.020
If you do it after your meetings, you won't get anything, you don't get, you can't get

00:27:21.020 --> 00:27:24.579
anything done because your brain is like, I don't know.

00:27:24.579 --> 00:27:28.619
As you're saying this Nahama, I'm like bursting and I'm sure, I know Jadie Ryan's on the call,

00:27:28.619 --> 00:27:32.540
she's probably thinking, she just mentioned Focusmate and Libby's going to talk about

00:27:32.540 --> 00:27:33.540
it.

00:27:33.540 --> 00:27:35.780
I love Focusmate, it's my BFF.

