There are several other platforms like that, but I see Curtis has a really great question

00:28:09.380 --> 00:28:10.900
and I would love him to ask it.

00:28:10.900 --> 00:28:12.900
Curtis, would you like to go?

00:28:12.900 --> 00:28:14.180
Yeah, sure.

00:28:14.180 --> 00:28:15.180
Howdy.

00:28:15.180 --> 00:28:19.020
This is a bit personal experience, but it also feels like a pretty universal experience

00:28:19.020 --> 00:28:24.579
for people who work in analytics and applied stats, that sort of thing.

00:28:24.579 --> 00:28:28.579
Can you talk a bit about your experience with strategies to help data science teams make

00:28:28.579 --> 00:28:34.219
a big impact across the org as they share their work?

00:28:34.219 --> 00:28:39.619
The way I like to frame it is you get asked by business leaders to do all this work, or

00:28:39.619 --> 00:28:42.660
maybe you discover something interesting and you're like, hey, this is a really good thing

00:28:42.660 --> 00:28:46.500
and I want to share it with another team or with leadership, but then it feels like you

00:28:46.500 --> 00:28:49.099
sometimes just toss it into a void.

00:28:49.099 --> 00:28:53.660
So based on your experience, what are good strategies to share?

00:28:53.660 --> 00:28:58.619
So a 20-minute presentation should have no more than four slides and shouldn't have any

00:28:58.619 --> 00:29:00.939
Greek on it at all.

00:29:00.939 --> 00:29:03.459
It probably shouldn't have any algorithm names either.

00:29:03.459 --> 00:29:05.060
I hate to say that, right?

00:29:05.060 --> 00:29:09.459
I've sat through a lot of presentations where people's goal is to show how smart they are.

00:29:09.459 --> 00:29:12.140
Your goal is to show how relevant you are.

00:29:12.140 --> 00:29:13.979
So I talked about business context.

00:29:13.979 --> 00:29:17.859
There's business context, there's this cool data integration stack, right, which POSIT

00:29:17.859 --> 00:29:22.660
sits into in my environment, and then there is seamless integration.

00:29:22.660 --> 00:29:28.020
So you need to take your business problem, your cool tech that you've solved, and then

00:29:28.020 --> 00:29:34.540
show end-to-end how it changes how the business does its work and how it has impact.

00:29:34.540 --> 00:29:39.459
And you need to go way to the beginning and way to the end, and you need to talk in terms

00:29:39.500 --> 00:29:46.260
that senior leaders are going to understand, cost, time, money, quality.

00:29:46.260 --> 00:29:47.260
And that's it.

00:29:47.260 --> 00:29:48.260
Nothing else, right?

00:29:48.260 --> 00:29:50.579
Not cool AI models, not whatever.

00:29:50.579 --> 00:29:54.500
You can throw in AI every so often because everyone wants to hear AI, but actually at

00:29:54.500 --> 00:29:58.619
this point, anything that involves a mean computation has been called AI.

00:29:58.619 --> 00:30:00.300
So I did a regression test.

00:30:00.300 --> 00:30:01.300
I did advanced AI.

00:30:01.300 --> 00:30:03.339
I'm like, go for it, right?

00:30:03.339 --> 00:30:11.180
But you need to frame it in that larger business context of what is the impact, and then how

00:30:11.180 --> 00:30:13.140
does it fit into a workflow?

00:30:13.140 --> 00:30:15.900
If people have to do, I just did this example for someone.

00:30:15.900 --> 00:30:16.900
I'm doing my job.

00:30:16.900 --> 00:30:17.900
I'm working, I'm working, I'm working.

00:30:17.900 --> 00:30:18.900
Okay, great.

00:30:18.900 --> 00:30:23.979
Now, I have to go do my analytics, and I come all the way over here, and I'm doing something

00:30:23.979 --> 00:30:25.699
over here, and I have to come back.

00:30:25.699 --> 00:30:28.260
And by the way, I'm throwing data back and forth.

00:30:28.260 --> 00:30:33.819
You will never have any impact because there's so much friction that nobody's ever going

00:30:33.819 --> 00:30:38.579
to turn their back and go off in this tiny little corner and get it back to the bigger

00:30:38.579 --> 00:30:39.579
picture.

00:30:39.579 --> 00:30:42.339
So make sure that your work is relevant.

00:30:42.339 --> 00:30:45.420
And if it takes you twice as long to do the project, take it twice as long.

00:30:45.420 --> 00:30:47.819
So that's how you sell the project.

00:30:47.819 --> 00:30:52.180
But the way you do to have impact is you pick a project.

00:30:52.180 --> 00:30:54.900
So when I take over a new data science team, I go shopping.

00:30:54.900 --> 00:30:57.380
I talk to all my friends and say, what do you need help with?

00:30:57.500 --> 00:30:58.500
What do you need help with?

00:30:58.500 --> 00:31:07.540
And then I find the project that has the most impact with the easiest to get to data and

00:31:07.540 --> 00:31:10.219
the person who is going to work with me the most.

00:31:10.219 --> 00:31:15.099
So there's a great book called Cascades on how to drive change.

00:31:15.099 --> 00:31:21.380
And what he says is, I'll put it in chat right now, but he says is, look, don't go worry

00:31:21.380 --> 00:31:24.339
about changing people who disagree with you.

00:31:24.339 --> 00:31:27.160
Go find your closest five friends.

00:31:27.939 --> 00:31:32.280
You get 10% of the organization to agree with you, 10 to 20%, and everyone's going to have

00:31:32.280 --> 00:31:33.280
to follow.

00:31:33.280 --> 00:31:36.839
They won't have any choice.

00:31:36.839 --> 00:31:42.239
So just pick the right problems and then pick your friends to work with.

00:31:42.239 --> 00:31:43.239
It's the mom test.

00:31:43.239 --> 00:31:46.400
Tell me what the mom test is, Eugene.

00:31:46.400 --> 00:31:48.359
If your mom can understand it, it's okay?

00:31:48.359 --> 00:31:53.160
No, there's a product book about when you sell.

00:31:53.160 --> 00:31:57.280
If you talk to your mom, if you talk to a bunch of people that are too close to you,

00:31:57.280 --> 00:32:00.000
they're always going to be too agreeable.

00:32:00.000 --> 00:32:04.000
So the whole book is based on that problem, that if you go to people you know all the

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:10.680
time, they may like the idea too much and not tell you the truth.

00:32:10.680 --> 00:32:13.160
So you have to go find a whole bunch of people you don't know.

00:32:13.160 --> 00:32:14.160
Yeah.

00:32:14.160 --> 00:32:19.280
Cascades says you have to find people who will challenge you.

00:32:19.280 --> 00:32:21.359
And I'm not that much of an agreeable mom.

00:32:21.359 --> 00:32:22.699
My kids will tell you.

00:32:23.239 --> 00:32:29.780
But you have to find people who will challenge you, but who will listen to you.

00:32:29.780 --> 00:32:32.540
So I am not, I'm driving a change in my organization.

00:32:32.540 --> 00:32:39.219
I am not going to go to the senior managers who are, in theory, the most influential.

00:32:39.219 --> 00:32:47.619
I'm going to the senior managers who like me because they're willing to consider it.

00:32:47.619 --> 00:32:49.500
So yeah, you need to think about it, right?

00:32:49.500 --> 00:32:53.300
You need to pick your good friends and not people who say, yeah, yeah, yeah, you're brilliant.

00:32:53.300 --> 00:32:56.140
They're the ones who say, okay, but let's talk about it.

00:32:56.140 --> 00:32:57.819
Let's work our way through it.

00:32:57.819 --> 00:32:58.819
Yeah.

00:32:58.819 --> 00:32:59.819
Thank you.

00:32:59.819 --> 00:33:05.060
So there was a question a little bit earlier in Slido, which was, at Pfizer, I imagine

00:33:05.060 --> 00:33:06.459
there's a lot of data.

00:33:06.459 --> 00:33:12.339
So how do you go about finding trends in the ocean of data?

00:33:12.339 --> 00:33:13.900
Okay.

00:33:13.900 --> 00:33:16.339
Data is not true by itself.

00:33:16.339 --> 00:33:18.739
Everyone's like, oh, the data will speak for itself.

00:33:18.979 --> 00:33:20.900
Have you guys all heard that?

00:33:20.900 --> 00:33:21.900
It's not true.

00:33:21.900 --> 00:33:23.300
They're lying to you.

00:33:23.300 --> 00:33:26.900
Data is only useful with respect to a question.

00:33:26.900 --> 00:33:31.300
So I walked people through the data lake this morning, and they were like, where do we find

00:33:31.300 --> 00:33:32.300
data?

00:33:32.300 --> 00:33:33.300
I'm like, blah, blah, blah.

00:33:33.300 --> 00:33:37.739
And they said, well, you know, and I said, look, you guys should all be able to do this

00:33:37.739 --> 00:33:40.140
by the end of the year.

00:33:40.140 --> 00:33:43.260
And I could tell there's this look of horror on their faces, like, are you out of your

00:33:43.260 --> 00:33:44.260
mind, Nechama?

00:33:44.260 --> 00:33:46.140
I'm like, no, go pick a question.

00:33:46.140 --> 00:33:47.140
Have a business question.

00:33:47.140 --> 00:33:48.140
So back to that question.

00:33:48.140 --> 00:33:54.020
You guys have a business question, hey, I wonder about, and then go find the data.

00:33:54.020 --> 00:33:57.780
And then go discover that the data lake has all the history data in it, so you have to

00:33:57.780 --> 00:34:01.260
get the current partition, right?

00:34:01.260 --> 00:34:05.380
If you ask a question and then go look for data, then you'll find something meaningful.

00:34:05.380 --> 00:34:12.020
If you just open up data and run an unsupervised learning thing, sure, you'll find something.

00:34:12.020 --> 00:34:16.379
But what you're going to find is that you're going to find correlations that don't make

00:34:16.379 --> 00:34:17.379
any sense.

00:34:17.379 --> 00:34:21.060
You're going to find that meat eaters have fewer children.

00:34:21.060 --> 00:34:25.260
That does not imply that meat consumption, that's how I always teach correlation, go

00:34:25.260 --> 00:34:30.139
look up by country meat consumption, inversely correlates to the number of children people

00:34:30.139 --> 00:34:35.239
have, because the minute you educate women, with the exception of yours, truly, they stop

00:34:35.239 --> 00:34:37.780
having children.

00:34:37.780 --> 00:34:42.139
And so meat consumption is a sign of wealth.

00:34:42.139 --> 00:34:46.020
Wealthier countries have fewer children per capita.

00:34:46.659 --> 00:34:49.540
But that does not mean that meat consumption is a contraceptive.

00:34:49.540 --> 00:34:52.419
So now you'll never forget what correlation means.

00:34:52.419 --> 00:34:56.300
I was just going to say, thank you so much for these examples, because it helps me remember

00:34:56.300 --> 00:35:00.979
all of these lessons so much, so much better.

00:35:00.979 --> 00:35:06.739
So what advice would you give to someone who is trying to build these bridges between siloed

00:35:06.739 --> 00:35:07.739
teams?

00:35:07.739 --> 00:35:13.699
Reach out to the most junior people and talk to them.

00:35:13.739 --> 00:35:18.300
No one wants to talk to the senior important person, but talk to the not important person,

00:35:18.300 --> 00:35:21.340
talk to the person who doesn't say anything in the meetings, or who says something and

00:35:21.340 --> 00:35:29.300
gets shut down, be kind, come up with ways to do favors, buy people coffee, send them

00:35:29.300 --> 00:35:35.500
Bravo cards or whatever it is that you do within your organization, like be human, right?

00:35:35.500 --> 00:35:39.419
Most people have stopped being human with the hybrid workplaces.

00:35:39.419 --> 00:35:42.939
We don't have to be face to face with anyone anymore.

00:35:43.659 --> 00:35:46.939
And just be nice to people.

00:35:46.939 --> 00:35:47.939
That's the first thing.

00:35:47.939 --> 00:35:50.500
And then be curious and ask questions and ask questions and ask questions.

00:35:50.500 --> 00:35:55.820
But if you go to someone and you see they're struggling in another silo, say, hey, you

00:35:55.820 --> 00:35:56.820
know what I saw?

00:35:56.820 --> 00:35:58.659
You really didn't understand this in a meeting.

00:35:58.659 --> 00:35:59.699
Let me help you.

00:35:59.699 --> 00:36:03.860
Can I help you understand where to find the data or how to do something?

00:36:03.860 --> 00:36:10.260
If you lead with an offer of help, almost no one says no.

00:36:10.260 --> 00:36:11.459
Almost no one's going to say no.

00:36:11.459 --> 00:36:19.139
And really, at the end of the day, I'm successful at Pfizer and any senior person is successful

00:36:19.139 --> 00:36:24.899
at Pfizer because of my ability to get things done outside of the official process.

00:36:24.899 --> 00:36:29.739
So we file tickets because you have to file a ticket, and then we can't find some information.

00:36:29.739 --> 00:36:34.500
So then we call up Jen R. Mike is laughing because he knows who I'm talking about.

00:36:34.500 --> 00:36:37.459
And she fixes it, right?

00:36:37.459 --> 00:36:41.939
And then two or three or four times a year, I send her boss this letter that says, oh,

00:36:41.939 --> 00:36:45.620
my God, she's the most amazing person in the world because she is.

00:36:45.620 --> 00:36:48.820
And she fixes any problems I have.

00:36:48.820 --> 00:36:54.060
And then when my co-workers who shouldn't be calling them up first, calling her up,

00:36:54.060 --> 00:36:57.979
call her up and waste her time, I stop that, right, because I don't want to waste her time.

00:36:57.979 --> 00:37:01.580
And I'm like, you guys help each other first, right?

00:37:01.580 --> 00:37:02.739
But that's how you break silos.

00:37:02.739 --> 00:37:05.500
So it's all about the relationships.

00:37:05.620 --> 00:37:07.860
It's all about the unofficial relationships.

00:37:07.860 --> 00:37:09.459
It's not about your title.

00:37:09.459 --> 00:37:15.179
The person who can help you the most if you need to influence a VP is who?

00:37:15.179 --> 00:37:18.459
His or her admin.

00:37:18.459 --> 00:37:20.899
They will stop you from being able to see that person.

00:37:20.899 --> 00:37:22.939
If you piss them off, forget it.

00:37:22.939 --> 00:37:24.100
You're never going to see that person.

00:37:24.100 --> 00:37:27.780
It doesn't matter if you report to him or not.

00:37:27.780 --> 00:37:28.500
I love it.

00:37:28.500 --> 00:37:30.659
Make friends with the gatekeepers, y'all.

00:37:30.659 --> 00:37:31.580
Yep.

00:37:31.580 --> 00:37:33.419
And make friends with the gatekeepers.

00:37:33.419 --> 00:37:39.260
Well, can we take a turn from people questions to technology questions and talk a little

00:37:39.260 --> 00:37:42.580
bit about your tool stack or your team's tool stack?

00:37:42.580 --> 00:37:43.100
Yeah.

00:37:43.100 --> 00:37:52.860
So my team is sitting on top of a data lake that I believe is Spark, but I don't actually,

00:37:52.860 --> 00:37:57.580
Snowflake, I don't actually care where the data lake is because that original data source

00:37:57.580 --> 00:37:59.820
has been morphed.

00:37:59.820 --> 00:38:01.300
And we're sitting in Databricks.

00:38:01.419 --> 00:38:07.379
So we use Databricks to control our data, and then we attach it to POSIT Workbench and

00:38:07.379 --> 00:38:14.820
POSIT Connect with GitHub, Jira, Confluence, et cetera, around the outside.

00:38:14.820 --> 00:38:16.540
And that allows us a couple things.

00:38:16.540 --> 00:38:21.659
The first of which is the Databricks environment gives us access both to the very controlled

00:38:21.659 --> 00:38:28.139
data and read-only and a read-write space that's common shared space, which is incredibly

00:38:28.139 --> 00:38:37.580
important because we will never have all of our data inside of the data lake, the official

00:38:37.580 --> 00:38:38.580
data lake.

00:38:38.580 --> 00:38:43.419
So that's just by the nature of the type of work I do, there will always be some data

00:38:43.419 --> 00:38:46.139
we're going to have to push in.

00:38:46.139 --> 00:38:52.780
We use POSIT because it's qualified and validated in our environment.

00:38:52.939 --> 00:39:00.139
And because I work in a large company, I have to partner with my IT department, and I actually

00:39:00.139 --> 00:39:04.139
have my environment called SPAR, S-P-A-R.

00:39:04.139 --> 00:39:06.780
I was in that kind of a mood that day.

00:39:06.780 --> 00:39:11.060
Someone asked me why, and I asked Vox for a bunch of – chat GPT for a bunch of names

00:39:11.060 --> 00:39:13.179
who call it Vox internally.

00:39:13.179 --> 00:39:18.979
And so Streamlined Platform for Analytics and Reporting is, I think, what SPAR stands

00:39:18.979 --> 00:39:19.979
for.

00:39:19.979 --> 00:39:24.500
And I convinced my IT department to own and support that platform.

00:39:24.500 --> 00:39:31.540
So they own the Databricks, the Databricks workspace, the POSIT connections, and the

00:39:31.540 --> 00:39:34.219
GitHub connections to the POSIT.

00:39:34.219 --> 00:39:39.820
And then I use their SDLC, a modified version of their SDLC validation process.

00:39:39.820 --> 00:39:46.659
So I validate my own code, which is a tenth of the cost and a hundredth of the time of

00:39:46.659 --> 00:39:49.860
having someone else do it.

00:39:50.739 --> 00:39:57.860
And now I've got a fully business-led, business-driven environment that's completely supported by

00:39:57.860 --> 00:40:01.340
IT, which is kind of like the Holy Grail.

00:40:01.340 --> 00:40:02.340
I don't know.

00:40:02.340 --> 00:40:03.860
I'm really excited I got to this place.

00:40:03.860 --> 00:40:04.939
I don't know if any of you guys are.

00:40:04.939 --> 00:40:07.260
I can't tell from the videos.

00:40:07.260 --> 00:40:12.260
But it's – to get digital, to think that they gave you the platform, IT to give you

00:40:12.260 --> 00:40:16.020
the platform, and then to be able to validate your own stuff.

00:40:16.020 --> 00:40:20.340
Before this, what we would have had to have done is go to an IT department and paid them

00:40:20.340 --> 00:40:25.939
$100,000 per app to push it through a validation process and add no value.

00:40:25.939 --> 00:40:31.939
And so that meant that we couldn't innovate anything because an app that took four weeks

00:40:31.939 --> 00:40:37.500
to write cost three employees in India to validate.

00:40:37.500 --> 00:40:38.699
And I couldn't justify it.

00:40:38.699 --> 00:40:40.100
So we never validated anything.

00:40:40.100 --> 00:40:42.100
And now we're validating things left and right.

00:40:42.100 --> 00:40:43.100
That's awesome.

00:40:43.100 --> 00:40:44.100
So it's partnership.

00:40:44.179 --> 00:40:49.179
So it's a tech stack with the process, with the validation process added to it.

00:40:49.179 --> 00:40:52.300
I have another tech tool question.

00:40:52.300 --> 00:40:54.300
I saw Roy asked in the chat.

00:40:54.300 --> 00:40:56.300
Roy, are you available to ask?

00:40:56.300 --> 00:40:57.300
Yeah.

00:40:57.300 --> 00:40:58.300
Hi.

00:40:58.300 --> 00:40:59.300
Thanks so much.

00:40:59.300 --> 00:41:00.300
Thanks for the talk so far.

00:41:00.300 --> 00:41:01.300
It's been great.

00:41:01.300 --> 00:41:06.060
So, you know, I'm thinking about, you know, the topic of the last two years, chat GPT

00:41:06.060 --> 00:41:07.820
and all these other tools.

00:41:07.820 --> 00:41:13.580
And so I'm trying to think forward five years into kind of the modern architecture of a

00:41:13.580 --> 00:41:15.419
analytic team.

00:41:15.419 --> 00:41:20.580
You talked a lot about how you want to know the business problem first and then write

00:41:20.580 --> 00:41:22.219
the code to do it.

00:41:22.219 --> 00:41:26.139
You know, I'm going to present this question as a little bit of a straw man.

00:41:26.139 --> 00:41:28.780
So I want to get your reaction.

00:41:28.780 --> 00:41:35.020
But you know, if I'm management, I say, well, you know, I'm going to hire a business guy.

00:41:35.020 --> 00:41:39.500
And then, you know, the LLM is going to write the code for the business guy.

00:41:39.500 --> 00:41:45.300
And you know, as long as they can use chat GPT, they can kind of write the appropriate

00:41:45.300 --> 00:41:46.300
code.

00:41:46.300 --> 00:41:50.620
And if you think about it from a budgetary standpoint, let's just say, you know, data

00:41:50.620 --> 00:41:54.699
scientists are more expensive than people with like, you know, on the business degree.

00:41:54.699 --> 00:41:58.540
So, you know, we're statisticians here for the most part.

00:41:58.540 --> 00:42:02.699
You know, we're kind of math and stats and coding first, then business second versus

00:42:02.860 --> 00:42:06.139
these guys, business first, math second, I guess.

00:42:07.820 --> 00:42:10.060
You know, what's the missing link in the logic?

00:42:10.939 --> 00:42:16.459
What are the managers maybe don't understand about kind of that stats focus first?

00:42:17.179 --> 00:42:17.419
Okay.

00:42:17.419 --> 00:42:19.340
So how far in the future do you think this is?

00:42:20.620 --> 00:42:24.939
I mean, I think the improvement is could be over the course of five years, 10 years.

00:42:24.939 --> 00:42:25.260
Okay.

00:42:25.260 --> 00:42:26.620
It's in my environment today.

00:42:27.260 --> 00:42:27.500
Right.

00:42:28.300 --> 00:42:28.620
Okay.

00:42:28.620 --> 00:42:29.820
So let's just be really clear.

00:42:29.820 --> 00:42:35.100
Right now I have business users who I put in front of Databricks.

00:42:35.100 --> 00:42:36.860
Now I don't put it in front of chat GPT.

00:42:36.860 --> 00:42:40.939
I put them in front of the Databricks AI assistant because it's tied to Unity catalog.

00:42:40.939 --> 00:42:44.459
So it understands the data and it only writes SQL and Python.

00:42:45.340 --> 00:42:46.699
Writes a little bit of R, right?

00:42:46.699 --> 00:42:52.139
But it basically writes SQL and Python for us and they can go and do exploratory data

00:42:52.139 --> 00:42:52.699
analysis.

00:42:53.419 --> 00:42:56.379
So that's the sad part of the situation, right?

00:42:56.379 --> 00:42:58.620
So the answer is the business people can go in and do it.

00:42:58.620 --> 00:43:02.540
The good news is that because the business people can go in and do that,

00:43:03.580 --> 00:43:08.379
they are able to frame what they need much better.

00:43:09.179 --> 00:43:12.459
So they can go in and build a proof of concept,

00:43:12.459 --> 00:43:20.699
Starman MVP that gets them 80% of what they want and it's not robust.

00:43:20.699 --> 00:43:26.219
Then I hand it to my programmers in India and say, here is my proof of concept MVP.

00:43:27.020 --> 00:43:30.620
Can you please show them how to write functional code,

00:43:31.820 --> 00:43:33.899
test driven tech, you know, development,

00:43:34.780 --> 00:43:37.179
put unit tests, all that type of stuff into it.

00:43:37.820 --> 00:43:40.459
So I don't think the business is ever going to write, you know,

00:43:40.459 --> 00:43:42.699
really strong, robust enterprise level code.

00:43:43.419 --> 00:43:48.060
I'm going to make a stab and say that most programmers I've met who don't fit in the

00:43:48.060 --> 00:43:53.820
professional programming space and many who have, Mike has seen some professional programs

00:43:53.820 --> 00:44:01.020
written by professional programmers that look like computer science student code, right?

00:44:03.899 --> 00:44:06.459
You know, it's like, can you write really strong code?

00:44:06.459 --> 00:44:13.820
But the real answer is that there is no flaw in that business logic.

00:44:15.979 --> 00:44:19.979
The people who were business last are going to have to become business first

00:44:20.939 --> 00:44:24.379
or they're going to have to become deeply technical.

00:44:24.939 --> 00:44:29.899
And what I mean by deeply technical, my oldest daughter's boyfriend does

00:44:32.300 --> 00:44:33.739
algorithms, right?

00:44:33.739 --> 00:44:36.620
Math algorithms for finance, right?

00:44:36.620 --> 00:44:39.419
That's a deep, you know, deep technical stuff, right?

00:44:39.419 --> 00:44:43.179
Finance, I know people who write, you know, programming languages,

00:44:43.179 --> 00:44:47.020
that level of PhD level comp sci, sure.

00:44:47.100 --> 00:44:48.860
There's still be a place for them.

00:44:48.860 --> 00:44:51.580
But just people to spit out SQL, no.

00:44:51.580 --> 00:44:54.860
And the good news, the good side of all of that, you guys,

00:44:54.860 --> 00:44:57.580
is that just spitting out SQL or Python is boring.

00:44:59.100 --> 00:45:02.139
Oh, would you please make a chart that does blah?

00:45:02.139 --> 00:45:03.979
And why didn't you make it green?

00:45:03.979 --> 00:45:06.459
And wait, no, I like blue better.

00:45:06.459 --> 00:45:12.139
And right, and reading 15 pages of requirements when someone could have drawn a picture.

00:45:12.780 --> 00:45:14.379
This is my numbing work.

00:45:14.699 --> 00:45:18.379
It's fun as an intern, maybe, because, like, I got to do something.

00:45:18.939 --> 00:45:21.100
But as you get more senior, it's mind numbing.

00:45:21.739 --> 00:45:25.340
And so when you get mind numbed, you end up going into management,

00:45:25.340 --> 00:45:26.379
which is even worse.

00:45:26.379 --> 00:45:28.540
Like, that's not the answer, right?

00:45:28.540 --> 00:45:30.459
Because now you're just babysitting people.

00:45:30.459 --> 00:45:35.820
So if you can figure out to Curtis's question of what are the business questions

00:45:35.820 --> 00:45:40.139
that the business needs to solve and help the business solve those questions

00:45:40.699 --> 00:45:42.939
and throw a little technology around it, because guess what?

00:45:43.020 --> 00:45:45.979
That AI assistant that helps my business user helps you, too.

00:45:47.500 --> 00:45:50.219
Nobody writes code as fast as an AI assistant.

00:45:51.580 --> 00:45:56.780
Because no one can keep track of 17 different programming syntax systems

00:45:56.780 --> 00:45:58.860
and date fields and everything else.

00:45:58.860 --> 00:46:02.540
So use the AI assistants, embrace them, but embrace the business,

00:46:02.540 --> 00:46:05.659
because you know what is possible.

00:46:05.659 --> 00:46:10.780
So you're driving a sports car and you're talking to people in a horse and buggy.

00:46:11.580 --> 00:46:14.300
You need to explain why they need that sports car.

00:46:15.500 --> 00:46:16.939
You don't need to drive the sports car.

00:46:16.939 --> 00:46:18.540
So that's what you can do is you can say,

00:46:18.540 --> 00:46:21.020
hey, look, I can get you someplace so much faster.

00:46:22.219 --> 00:46:26.219
I can get you someplace without having to stop and feed the horse every two hours.

00:46:28.139 --> 00:46:31.419
Or pick up poop or whatever it is that they're doing, right?

00:46:31.419 --> 00:46:36.699
So it's an opportunity for the technologist to learn the business to say,

00:46:36.699 --> 00:46:37.500
oh, guess what?

00:46:38.540 --> 00:46:39.500
I can do this.

00:46:39.820 --> 00:46:43.899
My IT consultants, I have a consulting company that works with me,

00:46:43.899 --> 00:46:47.820
and we were looking for some data about employees, which countries they work in.

00:46:47.820 --> 00:46:54.300
And he says, oh, there's an API within Pfizer that has employee locations.

00:46:55.979 --> 00:46:56.459
Cool.

00:46:56.459 --> 00:46:58.459
He just saved me a huge amount of trouble.

00:46:58.459 --> 00:46:59.340
He added value.

00:47:00.139 --> 00:47:01.979
You got to be the hero, right?

00:47:01.979 --> 00:47:03.340
He didn't write any code.

00:47:03.340 --> 00:47:04.379
He found the API.

00:47:04.379 --> 00:47:05.100
He sent it to us.

00:47:05.100 --> 00:47:06.860
We're like, cool, great, got a data source.

00:47:06.860 --> 00:47:07.820
Now we can be dangerous.

00:47:09.820 --> 00:47:10.300
Thank you.

00:47:11.260 --> 00:47:12.540
Did that answer your question, Roy?

00:47:13.979 --> 00:47:15.179
Yeah, thanks.

00:47:15.179 --> 00:47:15.739
Thanks so much.

00:47:15.739 --> 00:47:16.139
I did.

00:47:16.139 --> 00:47:16.860
I don't.

00:47:16.860 --> 00:47:21.659
Yes, I want to scare you because coding is no longer a career.

00:47:21.659 --> 00:47:23.739
It never really was, and it no longer is.

00:47:24.459 --> 00:47:28.379
As soon as they started outsourcing coding to cheaper geographies,

00:47:29.500 --> 00:47:31.739
it's not been a career for Americans.

00:47:31.739 --> 00:47:35.580
What Americans can do and people in the West can do

00:47:35.659 --> 00:47:40.060
is solve broad problems or wicked problems.

00:47:40.939 --> 00:47:42.939
I brand myself as a wicked problem solver.

00:47:42.939 --> 00:47:47.340
It can solve socially complicated problems where no one quite knows what they want,

00:47:47.340 --> 00:47:51.820
and no one can write a spec, but you can put the pieces together and solve a problem.

00:47:51.820 --> 00:47:53.100
That's what we can do.

00:47:53.979 --> 00:47:58.699
And you add a little code, there's some magic around it, and now you've got impact.

00:47:59.979 --> 00:48:01.820
And you can outperform a programmer.

00:48:02.459 --> 00:48:08.699
I can outperform 20 programmers because I can tell one person what actually has to be done,

00:48:08.699 --> 00:48:12.060
while the other 20 are still off running around in circles

00:48:12.060 --> 00:48:15.020
trying to get meaning out of data that they don't understand.

00:48:18.939 --> 00:48:23.899
It's amazing how fast this time can go by sometimes on Thursdays,

00:48:23.899 --> 00:48:30.300
but I see there's quite a conversation happening in the chat off of your question, Travis.

00:48:30.300 --> 00:48:34.620
So I thought it might be good to jump in here with that if you want to go next.

00:48:35.580 --> 00:48:38.060
And while he's doing that, I'm going to throw in some books,

00:48:38.860 --> 00:48:41.899
some links to some books that I think people should read.

