00:49:01.100 --> 00:49:05.100
I mean, basically, I prompted this conversation's happening in the chat by way of

00:49:06.060 --> 00:49:09.899
commenting that a lot of us seemingly not at Pfizer

00:49:09.899 --> 00:49:15.340
are still agonizing about the process of validating R work environments.

00:49:16.620 --> 00:49:20.379
I know there's a lot of good work in our validation hub regarding packages,

00:49:20.379 --> 00:49:24.780
but even just installing and maintaining R as a statistical computing environment,

00:49:25.580 --> 00:49:28.540
whether by way of Docker or we're talking in the chat about Nix.

00:49:29.500 --> 00:49:30.459
Other ways to do that.

00:49:31.659 --> 00:49:34.699
I was just curious if Pfizer has shared any of their experience,

00:49:34.699 --> 00:49:37.419
because what you described sounds like the dream world.

00:49:38.620 --> 00:49:42.540
Let's have Workbench stood up and hitting Databricks and it's all validated.

00:49:42.540 --> 00:49:42.939
Awesome.

