and just get someone to install that for me?

00:49:48.939 --> 00:49:53.340
So let me clarify a couple of things, okay?

00:49:53.340 --> 00:49:59.820
So there is validating for risk-based validation.

00:49:59.820 --> 00:50:02.540
So validating against a particular risk, right?

00:50:03.179 --> 00:50:10.219
So validating against output from an app against a regulatory submission,

00:50:10.939 --> 00:50:15.020
Mike Smith and I actually solved for now like two years ago.

00:50:15.020 --> 00:50:16.699
So there's a methodology for that.

00:50:16.699 --> 00:50:17.260
Call us up.

00:50:17.260 --> 00:50:18.540
We can tell you what to do.

00:50:18.540 --> 00:50:20.459
It's not proprietary.

00:50:20.459 --> 00:50:21.340
It's just what it is.

00:50:22.060 --> 00:50:24.699
Validating for workflow, which is what I'm doing,

00:50:25.419 --> 00:50:29.899
you show reproducibility, repeatability, evidence of QC,

00:50:29.899 --> 00:50:31.820
that you're doing unit testing.

00:50:31.820 --> 00:50:35.020
So either way, you guys, Pharma believes that

00:50:36.139 --> 00:50:42.300
the be-end and end-all of testing is UAT with screenshots, right?

00:50:43.260 --> 00:50:44.939
This is not testing, right?

00:50:44.939 --> 00:50:47.500
So write the code the right way.

00:50:47.500 --> 00:50:49.100
It's not that complicated.

00:50:49.100 --> 00:50:52.699
But what I would say is, I was just asked recently about,

00:50:52.699 --> 00:50:55.820
you know, how do you use open source versus not open source?

00:50:56.939 --> 00:51:01.820
Rachel, I would assume POSIT offers consulting services, I have no idea,

00:51:02.860 --> 00:51:06.459
that would help people build out these platforms.

00:51:06.459 --> 00:51:09.979
The principles of validation are, say what you're going to do,

00:51:09.979 --> 00:51:12.939
do what you said, prove you did what you said you were going to do.

00:51:12.939 --> 00:51:13.580
That's it.

00:51:14.699 --> 00:51:16.860
Pharma makes validation complicated.

00:51:17.820 --> 00:51:21.500
And by the way, a manual process is not validated either.

00:51:22.540 --> 00:51:30.459
So it's, and then become good, good friends with your process and quality people,

00:51:30.459 --> 00:51:31.340
because that's what I did.

00:51:31.340 --> 00:51:33.500
So you get agreement from process and quality,

00:51:33.500 --> 00:51:35.979
and then you get agreement from your IT department,

00:51:36.620 --> 00:51:38.139
and you build the relationships.

00:51:38.139 --> 00:51:41.260
And in my case, what I had to do was agree

00:51:41.260 --> 00:51:45.020
to do all of my data in a space where the data could be shared.

00:51:45.659 --> 00:51:47.899
So none of my data goes to S3 buckets.

00:51:49.260 --> 00:51:50.780
My data is all inside of Databricks.

00:51:50.780 --> 00:51:54.459
And they're like, look, you play where people can reuse what you're doing,

00:51:54.459 --> 00:51:57.100
will help you stand up a validation process.

00:51:57.100 --> 00:51:58.620
So it's a negotiation.

00:51:58.620 --> 00:52:02.459
And it's not, you need to believe it's possible,

00:52:02.459 --> 00:52:03.979
and then you need to build the relationships.

00:52:04.860 --> 00:52:05.979
That's really helpful.

00:52:05.979 --> 00:52:09.659
You do mention unit testing, which I'm curious about with regards to,

00:52:09.659 --> 00:52:12.300
I mean, I think a lot of us here know how to do unit testing for packages,

00:52:12.300 --> 00:52:12.860
for example.

00:52:13.820 --> 00:52:17.500
But what does a unit test for installing R look like?

00:52:17.500 --> 00:52:21.899
I mean, no, like R itself, because I get this question from SAS.

00:52:21.899 --> 00:52:23.580
How do we know SAS is actually SAS?

00:52:23.580 --> 00:52:24.620
And the same could apply to R.

00:52:24.620 --> 00:52:27.260
What do you do, like run a regression to make sure that you get the right answer?

00:52:28.219 --> 00:52:30.780
Does that validate that R is performing as expected?

00:52:31.340 --> 00:52:36.780
So in my case, my IT department runs the installing of packages and stuff.

00:52:36.780 --> 00:52:40.939
That's why I pay for POSIT rather than standing up my own environment.

00:52:40.939 --> 00:52:43.100
I'm paying my IT department to do that.

00:52:43.100 --> 00:52:46.620
Mike Smith, who's on this call, could talk to you forever about it.

00:52:46.620 --> 00:52:50.219
But it's the, I'm talking about unit testing for code you're writing, right?

00:52:50.219 --> 00:52:55.340
At some point, you have to assume that 1 plus 1 equals 2, unless it equals 11.

00:52:57.500 --> 00:53:02.459
And just, or whatever else, 1 plus 1 could equal 30 something, right?

00:53:02.459 --> 00:53:06.060
But yeah, just 9, I guess.

00:53:06.620 --> 00:53:07.979
I'm trying to do binary math.

00:53:07.979 --> 00:53:08.699
I should not do that.

00:53:09.100 --> 00:53:10.060
Understood.

00:53:10.060 --> 00:53:10.699
I appreciate it.

00:53:10.699 --> 00:53:11.340
Thank you.

